<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFFD0F59F79AF7ADC529F631" pageId="15" pageNumber="198" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFFD0F59F79AF7ADC529F631" blockId="15.[2057,2653,1746,2173]" lastBlockId="15.[1445,2652,2180,2844]" pageId="15" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFFD0F59F79AF7ADC571F78C" bold="true" box="[2058,2308,2066,2095]" pageId="15" pageNumber="198">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 63-82 mm, tail 91-115 mm, ear 13-18 mm, hindfoot 18-20 mm; weight 8-15 g. Rupp’s African Climbing Mouse is small, with very long prehensile tail. Tail is bicolored, darker above and paler below. Fur is long, soft, and brown or reddish-brown dorsally and white with dark gray bases ventrally. Base of each dorsal hairis dark gray. Black line runs mid-dorsally from neck to base oftail. Ears are relatively large and rounded. Limbs are adapted for climbing. Second to fourth digits of forelimbs have elongated claws, and first and fifth digits are greatly reduced. Hindlimb has second to fourth digits elongated,fifth digit long and opposable with a claw, and first digit greatly reduced.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFFD0F59FA37F627C595F61A" box="[1447,2528,2456,2489]" pageId="15" pageNumber="198" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFFD0F59FA37F627C595F61A" blockId="15.[1445,2652,2180,2844]" box="[1447,2528,2456,2489]" pageId="15" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFFD0F59FA37F627CA60F61A" bold="true" box="[1447,1557,2456,2489]" pageId="15" pageNumber="198">Habitat.</emphasis>
Only known from montane grasslands at elevations of 1800-1900 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
